B. Preprocessing (The Spark ML Way)
Spark ML algorithms cannot read standard columns. They require all input features to be combined into a single column (usually called "features"). You must memorize this flow: StringIndexer → VectorAssembler.

Python
from pyspark.ml.feature import StringIndexer, VectorAssembler

# 1. Convert categorical strings to numeric indexes (e.g., Department: "Sales" -> 1.0)
indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol="Department", outputCol="Dept_Index")
df_indexed = indexer.fit(df).transform(df)

# 2. Assemble all feature columns into one vector column
assembler = VectorAssembler(
    inputCols=["Age", "YearsAtCompany", "Dept_Index"], # Add your actual columns here
    outputCol="features"
)
final_data = assembler.transform(df_indexed)
C. Train/Test Split (Identical for both)
Python
train_data, test_data = final_data.randomSplit([0.8, 0.2], seed=42)
D. The Models (Classification vs. Regression)
You need to know how to instantiate and fit a model.

For Churn/Promotion (Classification):

Python
